I often use a cord layout instead of fixing myself to a screen res.
Try looking at http://www.md-drivingschool.co.uk to see what I mean.
Try resizing the window and changing text size. Basically it has a min
width of something like 400px, a max width of 100% (in other words the
screen width) and a default width defined in ems at a width the client
is happy with. Normally this default width is either the equivalent of
between 770px or 950px.

Mina and max width dont work in IE6 and earlier, so they just see a
fixed width page that scales up and down with text size. Poor them.
Everyone else sees a site that neatly fits into their window
regardless of how big or small their window is - this is because max
width kicks in to avoid horizontal scrolling.

Ok, I admit this layout type is kind of fluid because at smaller
screen sizes it does become fluid!
</POST>
<POST>
<POSTER> William &lt;toadwarr...@gmail.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-03T13:18:00 </POSTDATE>
I completely agree with Simon on window size. I think having higher
resolutions means having windows take up the whole screen is such a waste of
real estate. Especially if you're doing multiple things. With that in mind
800x600 probably gets used more than we may realise even if most new PCs are
sold with a default resolution higher than that.

I'd also agree with 1024. That's what I like to aim for and approximately
the size of my browsing window since there are a lot of sites that still
work around that size. It's a nice bonus that I'm left with a decent size of
desktop left beside the browser too.

William

